Based on personal travel experience, shifting my forecast again. Here are some observations: - While business travel was obviously light, it was clearly occurring. There appeared to be a conference last week in Portland, Maine and our hotel was solidly booked mid-week. Plenty of conference badges around. - Weekend travel was significant. The hotel breakfast bar on Friday, Saturday, and Sunday was overflowing. - Masks are optional outside of airports. Noses are fairly common in airports though. - Leisure travel appears to be primarily dominated by 50+ and those without kids. - I am receiving at least one "Wanna Get Away" e-mails per week with one-way prices of less than $100 across the entire US. Airline are clearly lowering prices to fill seats.

While I don't believe that passenger volume will dip to that level for a 3-day period, I do leave some chance for the unexpected - weather, war, enough State Governors locking down their populations to impact the numbers as a whole.

With current infections on the rise and traveller numbers hovering around the 2m mark, I can’t see the reduction to 1.3m any day, let alone for 3 days in a row, unless something drastic happens. But I struggle to see how the US would put the genie back in the bottle and go back into lockdown given that life has been continuing for many even when the case rates were high.

The ratio between the 2021 weekly average and the 2019 weekly average (I'm using weekly averages because there are significant variations that depend on day of week) has been growing from around 40% at the beginning of 2021 to around 80% in early July 2021, and has been stable around 80% since then. Modeling the projected values going forward at 80% of baseline (2019), and even at 70% doesn't result in any 3-day periods below 1.3M. I'm leaving 2% in Nov and 3% in Jan to account for historical lows due to seasonality, but I doubt they will happen. Need to track over time the ratio between 2021 and 2019.
